frameDefinitions: A Cognizer makes a Decision, which may be about an entity or a course of action.
A Cognizer faces a choice on some Issue.
An Agent decides temporarily not to perform a Desirable_action or not to interact with a Salient_entity.
A Cognizer would engage in an Activity if asked or otherwise prompted to do so.
A Speaker either agrees to or refuses to engage in a Proposed_action, proposed by an Interlocutor. '' 'They agreed to express their outrage with editorials in today's paper.'
A Protagonist delays a planned action because they cannot or do not want to proceed until an Expected_event occurs.
frameExamples: Dave Hayes <t>wavered</t> about moving to California because so many of his friends are in Baltimore.
I have actually <t>held off</t> on buying some movies by WB because of those damned cases.
The court is <t>willing</t> to depart from the usual range of sentencing .
They <t>agreed</t> to express their outrage with editorials in today's paper.
The cat <t>waited</t> on top of the washer as Elmer popped the lid off the can of cat food and then pounded the can's contents onto the plate
listRoleDefinitions: The <fen>Cognizer</fen> decides on a course of action.
<fen>Decision</fen> identifies the entity or course of action upon which the <fen>Cognizer</fen> decides.
The time or time period over which the <fen>Cognizer</fen> makes the decision.
The place where the <fen>Cognizer</fen> makes the decision.
The <fen>Cognizer</fen> is the person who repeatedly changes their mind about which of the <fen>Options</fen> to choose.
The <fen>Options</fen> are the alternative courses of action or the alternative physical or concrete entities that the <fen>Cognizer</fen> can choose from.
The <fen>Issue</fen> is a question about a course of action or a choice between items.

When there is an explicitly separate construal of the <fen>Options</fen>, <fen>Option_1</fen> is the first-mentioned alternative, typically in the form of a from-PP. When it is clear that  the <fen>Cognizer</fen> actually acted on their choice, <fen>Option_1</fen> is the alternative they embraced first before pursuing <fen>Option_2</fen>.

When there is an explicitly separate construal of the <fen>Options</fen>, <fen>Option_2</fen> is the second-mentioned alternative, typically in the form of a to-PP. When it is clear that  the <fen>Cognizer</fen> actually acted on their choice, <fen>Option_2</fen> is the alternative they embraced after abandoning <fen>Option_1</fen>.
This role denotes the <fen>Time</fen> interval during which the <fen>Cognizer</fen> keeps changing their mind about which of the <fen>Options</fen> to select.
This role identifies the <fen>Place</fen> where the <fen>Cognizer</fen> keeps changing their mind between the <fen>Options</fen> that present themselves.
The <fen>Agent</fen> decides not to engage in a <fen>Desirable_action</fen> for a while or not to interact with a <fen>Salient_entity</fen>.
<fen>Desirable_action</fen> identifies the event or activity in which the <fen>Agent</fen> does not engage for a while.
An entity that evokes a contextually inferrable <fen>Desirable_action</fen> that the <fen>Agent</fen> is temporarily forgoing.
This role identifies the interval of <fen>Time</fen> during which the the forgoing occurs.
This role identifies the <fen>Place</fen> where the temporary forgoing occurs.
The <fen>Cognizer</fen> is the individual that is willing to engage in the <fen>Activity</fen>.
The <fen>Activity</fen> is what the <fen>Cognizer</fen> would do under certain circumstances.
This role identifies the <fen>Time</fen> when the <fen>Cognizer</fen> is willing to engage in the <fen>Activity</fen>.
This role identifies the <fen>Place</fen> where the <fen>Cognizer</fen> is willing to engage in the <fen>Activity</fen>.
The <fen>Speaker</fen> is the person to whom a particular action has been proposed and who responds to the request or offer made.
This is the person who proposed the <fen>Proposed_action</fen>  to the <fen>Speaker</fen> and to whom the <fen>Speaker</fen> communicates  their response.
The <fen>Proposed_action</fen> is an action that the <fen>Speaker</fen> would perform if they were to accept or refuse the request or offer.
The time interval during which the <fen>Speaker</fen> makes their verbal response concerning the proposed action.
The location in which the <fen>Speaker</fen>  gives their verbal response to the proposed action.
The sentient being who cannot proceed with their planned activities until a Salient_entity has arrived or an Expected_event has occurred.
A concrete or abstract entity that the <fen>Protagonist</fen> expects to participate in an <fen>Expected_event</fen>, typically that of arriving at the <fen>Place</fen> of the <fen>Protagonist</fen>.
The <fen>Expected_event</fen> is an event that needs to take place or a state that needs to begin to hold before the <fen>Protagonist</fen> can proceed with their planned activities.
The time period during which the <fen>Protagonist</fen> is waiting.
The location in which the <fen>Protagonist</fen> is waiting.
listRoleExamples: <fex>Mo</fex> decided to quit the program.
Mo decided <fex>to quit the program</fex>.
The State Cabinet <fex>today</fex> decided to file an appeal in the Supreme Court seeking an extension of six months for implementation of its judgment
<fex>At the first</fex> crossroad we decided to wait.
<fex>I</fex> went back and forth over whether to post it or not, but the fact is that this blog is as much for you as it is for me.
In the late 1890s Carnegie vacillated <fex>between wanting to dominate the steel industry and wanting to sell out</fex>.
Editors go back and forth on a daily basis <fex>about what gets in the paper</fex>.
You've waffled <fex>from one explanation</fex> to another.
The heroine waffled from one plan <fex>to another</fex> and all of them were way out in 'left field'.

Here, however, the Romeros had provided some assurance to Ryan's mother of care,
although the court <fex>later</fex> waffled upon how much supervision was guaranteed
Do they know better than us that our dithering <fex>at the UN</fex> gave Saddam time to hide, destroy, and shuffle his weapons programs?
Instead, <fex>he</fex> held off on a public announcement of his decision for more than a year.
The board also waited <fex>with the appointment of seven members to the planning and zoning commission</fex> until a policy is set regarding requirements.
I ordered the blackberry cobbler with ice cream for dessert and held off <fex>on another pint</fex> as the rain kept coming down.

Saskatchewan teachers are not a happy lot as they had voted for a strike in June
<fex>then</fex> held off on it to give negotiations a chance during the summer.
<fex>My mom</fex> is very loath to take any drugs without medical supervision.
Does biology really matter more than a willingness <fex>to take an active role in a child's life</fex>?
<fex>He</fex> politely waited, hat in hand, until he could speak.
In busier times several passengers are waiting <fex>for the train</fex>.
